Yes. Given everything you've shown me over the last few days, I'd implement it differently.

The problem with the current approach is that it requires:

existsByCustomerId()

findSubscriptionDetails()

countAccountsBySubscriptionId()

sometimes findByCustomerId()


That's 3–4 database calls.


---

I'd reduce it to 2 queries.

Repository Query 1

Always fetch the subscription details for the customer, irrespective of the account.

@Query("""
    SELECT
        fs.customerId AS customerId,
        fs.registrationId AS registrationId,
        fs.subscriptionId AS subscriptionId
    FROM FedexSubscriptionEntity fs
    WHERE fs.customerId = :customerId
    """)
Optional<FedexSubscriptionProjection> findSubscription(String customerId);


---

Repository Query 2

Fetch account count and whether the requested account exists in one query.

@Query("""
    SELECT
        COUNT(fsa),
        SUM(
            CASE
                WHEN fsa.accountNumber = :accountNumber
                THEN 1
                ELSE 0
            END
        )
    FROM FedexSubscribedAccountsEntity fsa
    WHERE fsa.subscriptionId = :subscriptionId
    """)
Object[] getAccountStatistics(
        String subscriptionId,
        String accountNumber);

Or even better, return a projection:

public interface SubscriptionStatistics {

    Long getAccountCount();

    Long getMatchedAccount();
}


---

Then your service becomes very clean:

FedexSubscriptionProjection subscription = repository.findSubscription(customerId)
        .orElseThrow(...);

SubscriptionStatistics statistics =
        repository.getAccountStatistics(
                subscription.getSubscriptionId(),
                accountNumber);

FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse response =
        FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse.builder()
                .customerId(subscription.getCustomerId())
                .registrationId(subscription.getRegistrationId())
                .build();

if (statistics.getAccountCount() > 500) {
    response.setSubscriptionId(null);
    response.setAccountNumber(accountNumber);
    return response;
}

response.setSubscriptionId(subscription.getSubscriptionId());

if (statistics.getMatchedAccount() > 0) {
    response.setAccountNumber(accountNumber);
} else {
    response.setAccountNumber(null);
}

return response;


---

Why this is better

Only 2 database hits.

No repeated lookups.

No unnecessary existsByCustomerId() (the findSubscription() already tells you whether the customer exists).

No second findByCustomerId().

Very readable business flow.

Easy to unit test.

Easy to extend if the business rules change.



---

If I were reviewing this PR as a senior developer

I'd suggest removing existsByCustomerId() completely. It's an extra database round trip that doesn't add value because findSubscription(customerId) already answers the same question. Reducing unnecessary queries while keeping the service readable is generally the stronger implementation for a Spring Boot/JPA service.